00:02:42.350 --> 00:02:44.800
So let's start off by saying
that millions of babies

00:02:44.800 --> 00:02:47.540
are safely delivered in the
United States each year.

00:02:47.540 --> 00:02:51.070
Many women will experience
safe and healthy pregnancies

00:02:51.070 --> 00:02:53.360
and deliveries and
postpartum periods.

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:55.780
However, we are seeing
a startling trend

00:02:55.780 --> 00:02:57.190
in the United States.

00:02:57.190 --> 00:03:00.040
At a time when maternal
mortality is dropping

00:03:00.040 --> 00:03:02.050
in many places in
the world, death

00:03:02.050 --> 00:03:04.930
related pregnancy and
childbirth in the United States

00:03:04.930 --> 00:03:05.980
have increased.

00:03:05.980 --> 00:03:08.320
And the risk is
triple or quadruple

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:10.582
for black women in America.

00:03:10.582 --> 00:03:12.040
Today we're going
to look at what's

00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:15.013
driving that national trend
as well as the racial gap,

00:03:15.013 --> 00:03:16.930
and then we'll talk about
what we can actually

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:19.420
do about it because it's very
important to actually try

00:03:19.420 --> 00:03:20.860
to do something about it.

00:03:20.860 --> 00:03:23.800
To set the stage, let's take a
look at a video from ProPublica

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:26.620
which published an
amazing series with NPR

00:03:26.620 --> 00:03:28.750
about maternal
mortality in the US.

00:03:28.750 --> 00:03:30.220
And it's called Lost Mothers.

00:03:30.220 --> 00:03:31.968
Let's take a look.

00:03:31.968 --> 00:03:35.461
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:05:19.390 --> 00:05:21.100
TINA MARTIN: Wow.

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:25.600
That clip use statistics from
2016 and here we are in 2019.

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:27.970
Those stats are
still distressing

00:05:27.970 --> 00:05:30.310
and that clip itself
was disturbing.

00:05:30.310 --> 00:05:32.140
Wanda, give us an idea
of the big picture

00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:33.120
what's happening here.

00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:35.620
WANDA BARFIELD: Well, thank you
for your introduction, Tina,

00:05:35.620 --> 00:05:39.460
and thank you for your remarks
about this important issue.

00:05:39.460 --> 00:05:42.670
As been mentioned by Tina
and also by the clip,

00:05:42.670 --> 00:05:47.620
that we see about 700 women
dying each year in our country

00:05:47.620 --> 00:05:50.950
due to pregnancy or
delivery complications.

00:05:50.950 --> 00:05:53.260
With better data and
collection techniques

00:05:53.260 --> 00:05:55.840
we're getting better
and better in terms

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:58.960
of identifying the causes
of these deaths that

00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:02.290
are truly related to
pregnancy as well as delivery.

00:06:02.290 --> 00:06:05.620
But while pregnancy
related mortality ratios

00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:09.110
have been relatively stable
in the last few years,

00:06:09.110 --> 00:06:11.500
we know that overall
pregnancy related

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:14.180
mortality has not decreased.

00:06:14.180 --> 00:06:16.610
And this really is
a cause for concern.

00:06:16.610 --> 00:06:19.270
And another major
cause for concern

00:06:19.270 --> 00:06:22.330
are these evident racial
disparities that we're seeing.

00:06:22.330 --> 00:06:27.010
So for more than 30 years we've
seen a disproportionate burden

00:06:27.010 --> 00:06:29.620
of death among
African-American women.

00:06:29.620 --> 00:06:32.830
Today, black women are
almost four times as

00:06:32.830 --> 00:06:36.220
likely to die of a pregnancy
related complication

00:06:36.220 --> 00:06:38.500
compared to white women.

00:06:38.500 --> 00:06:41.560
And this is really an
unconscionable issue.

00:06:41.560 --> 00:06:45.655
Importantly, emerging data from
state based maternal mortality

00:06:45.655 --> 00:06:47.200
review committees--
and these are

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:50.410
groups that come together
to try to understand

00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:52.570
the causes of death
--they're showing

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:57.560
that 60% of maternal
deaths may be preventable.

00:06:57.560 --> 00:06:59.530
And so we have no
reason to believe

00:06:59.530 --> 00:07:03.650
that this prevent abilities
that would vary by race.

00:07:03.650 --> 00:07:06.010
So we have a lot of
room for opportunities

00:07:06.010 --> 00:07:08.350
for intervention in this area.

00:07:08.350 --> 00:07:12.070
Better data can also help
us to better understand

00:07:12.070 --> 00:07:15.070
the gaps and the drivers
of maternal deaths

00:07:15.070 --> 00:07:18.350
and think about ways
that we can prevent them.

00:07:18.350 --> 00:07:21.460
So some of what we're seeing
from these review committees

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:25.060
are that there are underlying
chronic conditions that

00:07:25.060 --> 00:07:28.420
are disparate particularly
for African-American women.

00:07:28.420 --> 00:07:32.020
We're seeing that there are
the effects of unconscious bias

00:07:32.020 --> 00:07:34.780
as well as structural racism
that may be contributing

00:07:34.780 --> 00:07:36.190
to these deaths.

00:07:36.190 --> 00:07:38.590
And then the third issue
is an issue of quality.

00:07:38.590 --> 00:07:41.290
We're seeing variation
in hospital quality.

00:07:41.290 --> 00:07:43.030
So with a better
data we're going

00:07:43.030 --> 00:07:45.250
to get better
understanding of what

00:07:45.250 --> 00:07:48.490
we need to do in terms of
quality care initiatives

00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:50.840
that may have better impact.

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:53.500
We can also think about
standardized care that

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:57.220
will allow women to get the
right care at the right time

00:07:57.220 --> 00:07:58.570
and the right place.

00:07:58.570 --> 00:08:02.170
And high quality care is
really an important factor

00:08:02.170 --> 00:08:06.130
in trying to improve the care of
women not only in the hospital,

00:08:06.130 --> 00:08:10.520
but thinking about care into
the year after delivery.

00:08:10.520 --> 00:08:14.650
So we have a real opportunity to
really improve maternal health.

00:08:14.650 --> 00:08:18.520
At CDC we're really trying to
see how we can improve data

00:08:18.520 --> 00:08:20.050
across the country.

00:08:20.050 --> 00:08:23.180
And we have an opportunity
now with the support

00:08:23.180 --> 00:08:26.720
through Congress to look at
maternal mortality review

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:27.340
committees.

00:08:27.340 --> 00:08:29.380
And so states and
jurisdictions will

00:08:29.380 --> 00:08:34.140
have an opportunity to
improve their care for women.

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:37.059
And at this point
I'd like to stop

00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:39.610
and I'll give a
chance for Dr. Langer

00:08:39.610 --> 00:08:41.152
to further the discussion.

00:08:41.152 --> 00:08:41.860
TINA MARTIN: Yes.

00:08:41.860 --> 00:08:44.680
Because you study health
trends around the world.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:47.485
Help us to put this into global
context what's happening here

00:08:47.485 --> 00:08:48.360
in the United States.

00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:49.090
ANA LANGER: Sure.

00:08:49.090 --> 00:08:51.960
Thank you so much
for that question.

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:54.820
Those of us working on
global maternal health

00:08:54.820 --> 00:08:58.490
always considered maternal
mortality and severe morbidity

00:08:58.490 --> 00:09:01.430
as a problem of low
resource settings.

00:09:01.430 --> 00:09:05.380
In fact, after all,
99% of maternal deaths

00:09:05.380 --> 00:09:07.820
happen in low and
middle income countries,

00:09:07.820 --> 00:09:12.030
but that remaining 1% happens
among vulnerable women

00:09:12.030 --> 00:09:13.630
in developed countries.

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:17.560
And in fact the US is a country
where most of those deaths

00:09:17.560 --> 00:09:21.310
happen, and probably
the only one, in fact

00:09:21.310 --> 00:09:23.800
the only developed country
where the maternal mortality

00:09:23.800 --> 00:09:27.340
ratio is going up.

00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:31.930
Overall, if you list
the countries from one

00:09:31.930 --> 00:09:34.150
with the lowest maternal
mortality ratio, which

00:09:34.150 --> 00:09:36.730
is Finland, to the
one with the highest,

00:09:36.730 --> 00:09:40.710
the US occupies at
place number 46.

00:09:40.710 --> 00:09:44.320
In fact, it's interesting
to see that the US is

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:48.040
below Qatar, Libya,
and of course

00:09:48.040 --> 00:09:51.070
all Western European
countries, but Qatar and Libya

00:09:51.070 --> 00:09:53.050
are countries with a
much smaller economy

00:09:53.050 --> 00:09:56.430
and expenditures in health.

00:09:56.430 --> 00:09:58.750
But as Wanda
correctly pointed out,

00:09:58.750 --> 00:10:01.130
these deaths don't
happen randomly.

00:10:01.130 --> 00:10:03.640
So if you look at
maternal mortality

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:06.220
among non-Hispanic black
women and compare it

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:09.530
with what's happening
in other countries,

00:10:09.530 --> 00:10:12.100
you will see that
maternal mortality

00:10:12.100 --> 00:10:14.500
among non-Hispanic
black women here

00:10:14.500 --> 00:10:17.110
is higher than maternal
mortality in Mexico,

00:10:17.110 --> 00:10:19.300
and is the same
one as in Malaysia,

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:23.680
countries you wouldn't think
are doing better than America.

00:10:23.680 --> 00:10:25.960
On the other hand, if you
look at maternal mortality

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:28.390
among non-Hispanic
white women, you

00:10:28.390 --> 00:10:31.930
will see that the ratio is
above the national ratio

00:10:31.930 --> 00:10:33.720
in New Zealand and the UK.

00:10:33.720 --> 00:10:37.770
But vary slightly so,
almost at the same level.

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:41.860
At the first report we'll
draw our recent attention

00:10:41.860 --> 00:10:46.120
at least to this topic came
mostly from human rights

00:10:46.120 --> 00:10:46.990
organizations.

00:10:46.990 --> 00:10:49.450
There was this very
important report

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:53.710
from Amnesty International,
and in 2011 it

00:10:53.710 --> 00:10:55.900
called deadly delivery,
the maternal health

00:10:55.900 --> 00:10:58.270
crisis in the US,
and from journalists,

00:10:58.270 --> 00:11:02.920
and you showed that clip from
Nina Martin and ProPublica

00:11:02.920 --> 00:11:04.120
and NPR.

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:06.700
But now more
academics, obviously

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:09.520
professional associations,
the CDC and so many

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:14.260
others are doing more studies
and publishing more papers,

00:11:14.260 --> 00:11:18.070
academic papers on this issue
trying to understand what's

00:11:18.070 --> 00:11:20.230
behind the numbers
and trying to come up

00:11:20.230 --> 00:11:25.950
with solutions for the crisis
that we are now facing.

00:11:25.950 --> 00:11:30.150
So the drivers, as Wanda
already pointed out,

00:11:30.150 --> 00:11:33.100
include lack of
access, poor quality,

00:11:33.100 --> 00:11:38.140
and in fact a basic societal
undervaluing of women of color

00:11:38.140 --> 00:11:40.780
that we are also trying
to understand better

00:11:40.780 --> 00:11:44.860
the reasons for everything
that comes with it.

00:11:44.860 --> 00:11:48.340
So the US I think can
learn from other countries.

00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:52.240
We've been quite successful in
making maternal mortality come

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:54.170
down in many other places.

00:11:54.170 --> 00:11:56.850
So I look forward to maybe
giving some examples later

00:11:56.850 --> 00:11:57.350
about that.

00:11:57.350 --> 00:11:58.840
TINA MARTIN: Excellent.

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:00.730
Haywood, during your
time as president

00:12:00.730 --> 00:12:03.940
of ACOG you advocated
for policy change that

00:12:03.940 --> 00:12:05.860
can improve the state
of maternity care

00:12:05.860 --> 00:12:07.270
in the United States.

00:12:07.270 --> 00:12:09.570
Tell us a little bit
more about that work.

00:12:09.570 --> 00:12:12.160
And listening to you
earlier, we talked

00:12:12.160 --> 00:12:15.470
about social determinants
of health and hearing Ana

00:12:15.470 --> 00:12:20.470
saying undervaluing women of
color or patients of color.

00:12:20.470 --> 00:12:23.860
So what is your
perspective on that?

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:25.690
HAYWOOD BROWN:
Well, at ACOG we've

00:12:25.690 --> 00:12:28.450
been focused on
maternal mortality

00:12:28.450 --> 00:12:32.920
and near misses for
many years recognizing

00:12:32.920 --> 00:12:36.730
the causes for maternal death,
but also recognizing the risk

00:12:36.730 --> 00:12:39.990
factors for maternal
morbidity, maternal death.

00:12:39.990 --> 00:12:43.220
And let me say from the outset,
for every maternal death there

00:12:43.220 --> 00:12:45.220
are about 60 near misses.

00:12:45.220 --> 00:12:48.640
And those near misses include
things like hemorrhage

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:51.040
that didn't lead to
death, heart failure

00:12:51.040 --> 00:12:53.135
didn't need to death,
a blood clot that

00:12:53.135 --> 00:12:54.760
didn't lead to death,
an infection that

00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:56.060
didn't lead to death.

00:12:56.060 --> 00:12:58.120
And so by understanding
these type of things

00:12:58.120 --> 00:13:00.350
it's been very,
very helpful for us.

00:13:00.350 --> 00:13:03.000
And we've looked at this
over the course of years.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.980
So one of the things
that I focused on

00:13:05.980 --> 00:13:09.220
over the past couple of
years is to really push

00:13:09.220 --> 00:13:13.720
for maternal mortality reviews,
and we spent a lot of time

00:13:13.720 --> 00:13:17.410
on Capitol Hill, and as
Dr. Barfield has indicated

00:13:17.410 --> 00:13:21.160
we did get legislation passed
this year called the Preventing

00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:24.340
Maternal Death Act and
Maternal Health Accountability

00:13:24.340 --> 00:13:26.390
Act that was signed into law.

00:13:26.390 --> 00:13:28.870
And the idea was
that every state

00:13:28.870 --> 00:13:31.510
would have a maternal mortality
review so we could better

00:13:31.510 --> 00:13:36.220
understand the causes of
pregnancy related death.

00:13:36.220 --> 00:13:39.160
There was going to be
some financial support

00:13:39.160 --> 00:13:42.610
for the infrastructure
for states who did not

00:13:42.610 --> 00:13:45.610
have a mature review
program, and also

00:13:45.610 --> 00:13:47.500
for those states
who had one to try

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:50.060
to strengthen those program.

00:13:50.060 --> 00:13:52.168
The other things that
we did were focus on

00:13:52.168 --> 00:13:54.460
levels of care, which Susan
will talk a little bit more

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:57.610
about, recognizing
the fact that there

00:13:57.610 --> 00:13:59.170
are things that we could do.

00:13:59.170 --> 00:14:01.385
There were interventions
that we should have.

00:14:01.385 --> 00:14:03.010
And I will talk a
little bit about this

00:14:03.010 --> 00:14:06.310
later if I have time,
but access to care

00:14:06.310 --> 00:14:10.020
is still a major issue
in the United States.

00:14:10.020 --> 00:14:12.250
Many of us live in
rural communities

00:14:12.250 --> 00:14:14.410
and we'll talk a little
bit about the fact

00:14:14.410 --> 00:14:21.010
that access is a serious factor
for women to have to travel

00:14:21.010 --> 00:14:23.260
to distances and so forth.

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:26.440
And the other factor, of course,
is that fragmentation of care

00:14:26.440 --> 00:14:29.320
where the provider and
the delivery facility

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:30.560
are very different.

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:33.440
And so those also impact issues.

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:35.818
And with that these
are the type of things

00:14:35.818 --> 00:14:38.110
that we've talked about this
year and we've emphasized.

00:14:38.110 --> 00:14:41.300
We've emphasized the
challenges of access.

00:14:41.300 --> 00:14:44.360
We've emphasized the importance
of doing the reviews.

00:14:44.360 --> 00:14:47.695
We've emphasized
levels of care where

00:14:47.695 --> 00:14:51.610
a person would communicate
from a rural community

00:14:51.610 --> 00:14:54.880
to a more tertiary care center,
certain types of patients

00:14:54.880 --> 00:14:58.630
who may be much more
appropriate to be transferred.

00:14:58.630 --> 00:15:02.050
An example would be a lady
with a placental abnormality

00:15:02.050 --> 00:15:06.077
with a placenta previa which
is at high risk for hemorrhage.

00:15:06.077 --> 00:15:07.660
And even though they
may be able to do

00:15:07.660 --> 00:15:09.700
a cesarean at that
facility, they

00:15:09.700 --> 00:15:13.090
may not have the blood to
handle the volume of blood loss.

00:15:13.090 --> 00:15:15.910
And so those are the kind
of challenges and things

00:15:15.910 --> 00:15:20.290
that we focused on to
improve the quality of care

00:15:20.290 --> 00:15:23.800
and improved outcomes
for all women.

00:15:23.800 --> 00:15:28.730
Dr. Barfield also mentioned
the fact that as we do reviews,

00:15:28.730 --> 00:15:31.060
we've clearly noticed
this increasing

00:15:31.060 --> 00:15:33.110
trend over the last 20 years.

00:15:33.110 --> 00:15:35.560
Part of that has been due
to better ascertainment,

00:15:35.560 --> 00:15:37.510
but part of it is
also due to the fact

00:15:37.510 --> 00:15:42.310
that women are indeed dying more
often over the last 20 years,

00:15:42.310 --> 00:15:44.050
particularly women of color.

00:15:44.050 --> 00:15:45.610
TINA MARTIN: Thank you.

00:15:45.610 --> 00:15:47.670
We will definitely
delve more into that.

00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:49.460
Susan, let's talk
to you for a second.

00:15:49.460 --> 00:15:51.400
You're an OBGYN and
you have delivered

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:52.930
more than 4,000 babies.

00:15:52.930 --> 00:15:53.515
Is that true?

00:15:53.515 --> 00:15:54.640
SUSAN MANN: Probably 5,000.

00:15:54.640 --> 00:15:56.590
TINA MARTIN: More
than 5,000 babies?

00:15:56.590 --> 00:15:57.950
Oh my goodness.

00:15:57.950 --> 00:15:58.450
All right.

00:15:58.450 --> 00:15:59.140
And counting.

00:15:59.140 --> 00:15:59.772
OK.

00:15:59.772 --> 00:16:02.230
So you know firsthand what
these mothers are going through.

00:16:02.230 --> 00:16:04.900
And you recently
published a study

00:16:04.900 --> 00:16:06.610
co-authored by
Haywood and others

00:16:06.610 --> 00:16:10.300
about how to make changes
quickly in hospital settings

00:16:10.300 --> 00:16:12.340
to prevent maternal mortality.

00:16:12.340 --> 00:16:13.240
Talk about that.

00:16:13.240 --> 00:16:13.948
SUSAN MANN: Sure.

00:16:13.948 --> 00:16:17.690
Thank you very much and thank
you forum for inviting me.

00:16:17.690 --> 00:16:20.050
I have been practicing
very comfortably here

00:16:20.050 --> 00:16:23.500
at Beth Israel in Boston
for the past 30 years.

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:29.120
And I've had the honor of seeing
a lot of changes over time.

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:32.980
Around the early 2000s
the Department of Defense

00:16:32.980 --> 00:16:34.930
came to Beth Israel
and said we want

00:16:34.930 --> 00:16:37.750
to work with you to
start studying teamwork

00:16:37.750 --> 00:16:40.210
and communication
among disciplines

00:16:40.210 --> 00:16:43.780
and see if we can impart some
of the knowledge we've gained

00:16:43.780 --> 00:16:46.010
from the military to medicine.

00:16:46.010 --> 00:16:49.120
And so that really became
a strong interest of mine,

00:16:49.120 --> 00:16:53.500
and we started foundational work
that really changed how people

00:16:53.500 --> 00:16:56.830
practice and communicate in
hospitals across the United

00:16:56.830 --> 00:16:59.530
States and outside
the United States.

00:16:59.530 --> 00:17:04.180
And when the increase
in maternal mortalities

00:17:04.180 --> 00:17:06.250
continued to go up
during this period,

00:17:06.250 --> 00:17:09.430
I was a little bit baffled
and obviously quite concerned.

00:17:12.130 --> 00:17:15.490
I was asked by a hospital
system in South Dakota

00:17:15.490 --> 00:17:18.369
that I was doing work
for to come out and see

00:17:18.369 --> 00:17:21.130
if I could help them improve
their communication with some

00:17:21.130 --> 00:17:24.460
of their rural hospitals and
critical access hospitals.

00:17:24.460 --> 00:17:27.280
And as I mentioned, it's
a real different world

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:31.600
out in rural health compared to
what I'd been living in Boston.

00:17:31.600 --> 00:17:34.210
I joke that if I sneeze
there about four people

00:17:34.210 --> 00:17:35.963
to hand me a Kleenex.

00:17:35.963 --> 00:17:38.380
If you're in a rural hospital
you're waiting for the truck

00:17:38.380 --> 00:17:40.420
to come to deliver the Kleenex.

00:17:40.420 --> 00:17:42.580
So it's quite a
different experience.

00:17:42.580 --> 00:17:44.380
And so when I
said, well, tell me

00:17:44.380 --> 00:17:47.980
about some of these hospitals
with a system of 17 hospitals.

00:17:47.980 --> 00:17:51.220
They said, well, some of
them are really quite small.

00:17:51.220 --> 00:17:52.765
And I said, how small are they?

00:17:52.765 --> 00:17:56.290
They said, well, some of
them do 50 deliveries a year.

00:17:56.290 --> 00:17:57.190
And I said, wow.

00:17:57.190 --> 00:17:59.020
That's a delivery a week.

00:17:59.020 --> 00:18:03.070
How can you be good at
doing a delivery a week?

00:18:03.070 --> 00:18:06.730
And I said, well, obviously you
should close those hospitals.

00:18:06.730 --> 00:18:08.830
And they said, well,
Susan, we would,

00:18:08.830 --> 00:18:12.430
but then a woman might need to
drive six hours to have a baby.

00:18:12.430 --> 00:18:16.625
I said you need to leave
those hospitals open

00:18:16.625 --> 00:18:18.270
and you need to
make them better.

00:18:18.270 --> 00:18:20.290
And she said, that's
why we called you.

00:18:20.290 --> 00:18:24.340
So being a good researcher
I called my friend Wanda

00:18:24.340 --> 00:18:26.270
and I said, Wanda,
where are people dying?

00:18:26.270 --> 00:18:28.540
Are they dying in these
small rural hospitals?

00:18:28.540 --> 00:18:31.647
Are we able to get them to
academic medical centers?

00:18:31.647 --> 00:18:32.230
This was what?

00:18:32.230 --> 00:18:33.740
Six, seven, eight years ago.

00:18:33.740 --> 00:18:37.180
And she said we just don't
have great data, because

00:18:37.180 --> 00:18:41.050
at that point in time how we
were collecting data oftentimes

00:18:41.050 --> 00:18:43.750
would be a checkbox on
a death certificate.

00:18:43.750 --> 00:18:45.520
We weren't always
linking it to births.

00:18:48.790 --> 00:18:51.370
And then the address
also, you couldn't quite

00:18:51.370 --> 00:18:53.140
tell where they were dying.

00:18:53.140 --> 00:18:56.060
And she said, actually, Susan,
I really hate to tell you this,

00:18:56.060 --> 00:19:00.040
but I think quite a few occur
outside of the hospital.

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:05.830
And so you look at opioid abuse
and domestic violence, suicide,

00:19:05.830 --> 00:19:06.880
and all those issues.

00:19:06.880 --> 00:19:07.570
And I said, wow.

00:19:07.570 --> 00:19:08.930
Those are really big issues.

00:19:08.930 --> 00:19:11.350
I'm just a practicing
obstetrician gynecologist.

00:19:11.350 --> 00:19:13.210
I don't know that
I can tackle that,

00:19:13.210 --> 00:19:15.400
but I certainly can
look into what is it

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:17.480
that we do in our hospitals?

00:19:17.480 --> 00:19:20.560
How can we be better
prepared and how do we

00:19:20.560 --> 00:19:23.000
get all hospitals to do this?

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.630
And so in a recent
article that I

00:19:25.630 --> 00:19:29.320
wrote with Haywood and the
current president Lisa Allea

00:19:29.320 --> 00:19:33.400
and Kim McKay who's my
colleague out in South Dakota,

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:36.730
we were really looking at how
do you introduce these concepts

00:19:36.730 --> 00:19:38.320
to all hospitals?

00:19:38.320 --> 00:19:40.300
And what we wanted
to focus on were

00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:44.980
the top three preventable causes
of pregnancy related deaths.

00:19:44.980 --> 00:19:48.220
And that includes severe
hypertension and management

00:19:48.220 --> 00:19:51.400
even after they go home;
Postpartum hemorrhage

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:54.790
as we saw so many of those
women in that clip died from;

00:19:54.790 --> 00:19:57.460
and then also
preventing blood clots.

00:19:57.460 --> 00:20:00.730
I'm sure you heard about Serena
Williams and the troubles

00:20:00.730 --> 00:20:01.360
that she had.

00:20:01.860 --> 00:20:05.980
So we really wanted to
focus on what can be done,

00:20:05.980 --> 00:20:08.710
how to improve teamwork
and communication.

00:20:08.710 --> 00:20:12.370
And also these levels of care,
that Haywood was talking about.

00:20:12.370 --> 00:20:15.520
If you identify somebody
that's at three C sections,

00:20:15.520 --> 00:20:17.710
and needs to have a
fourth, should she really

00:20:17.710 --> 00:20:21.090
be done in a hospital that
does one delivery a week?

00:20:21.090 --> 00:20:23.720
She needs to be identified
and [? risked ?]

00:20:23.720 --> 00:20:26.000
out to a higher level of care.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.160
Whether she'll go there
is a different topic,

00:20:28.160 --> 00:20:30.620
because women make their
own choices in life.

00:20:30.620 --> 00:20:33.920
But it should be up to us
still at least educator her,

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:36.290
and say, we have connections.

00:20:36.290 --> 00:20:37.790
We send our babies
out, when they're

00:20:37.790 --> 00:20:40.190
28 weeks, to these hospitals.

00:20:40.190 --> 00:20:42.440
We should have these kind
of connections for our moms,

00:20:42.440 --> 00:20:43.578
as well.

00:20:43.578 --> 00:20:45.620
TINA MARTIN: We're going
to get into all of that.

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:48.410
I just want to make sure that
we're connecting with Karen.

00:20:48.410 --> 00:20:50.245
Dr. Scott are you there?

00:20:50.245 --> 00:20:51.120
KAREN SCOTT: Yes, hi.

00:20:51.120 --> 00:20:51.570
TINA MARTIN: You can hear us.

00:20:51.570 --> 00:20:52.020
KAREN SCOTT: Good morning, Tina.

00:20:52.020 --> 00:20:52.510
TINA MARTIN: Excellent.

00:20:52.510 --> 00:20:53.390
KAREN SCOTT: Good
morning, panel.

00:20:53.390 --> 00:20:54.473
TINA MARTIN: Good morning.

00:20:54.473 --> 00:20:55.640
Good morning.

00:20:55.640 --> 00:20:59.060
In your role at the California
Birth Equity Collaborative

00:20:59.060 --> 00:21:03.200
and the California Maternal
Quality Care Collaborative,

00:21:03.200 --> 00:21:07.460
you've really taken direct
aim at some of the disparities

00:21:07.460 --> 00:21:08.580
that we've talked about.

00:21:08.580 --> 00:21:10.545
So tell us a little
bit about your work.

00:21:10.545 --> 00:21:11.420
KAREN SCOTT: Yes, hi.

00:21:11.420 --> 00:21:12.360
Thank you so much.

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:15.350
So the California Maternal
Quality Care Collaborative,

00:21:15.350 --> 00:21:20.090
CMQCC, is a multi-stakeholder
organization

00:21:20.090 --> 00:21:22.280
working closely with state
and national partners

00:21:22.280 --> 00:21:25.470
to reduce preventable causes
of maternal mortality,

00:21:25.470 --> 00:21:28.260
maternal morbidity, and racial
disparities in California.

00:21:28.260 --> 00:21:33.350
CMQCC uses research, QI
toolkits, statewide outreach

00:21:33.350 --> 00:21:36.140
collaboratives, and its
innovative maternal data center

00:21:36.140 --> 00:21:39.090
to improve health outcomes
for mothers and infants.

00:21:39.090 --> 00:21:43.220
CMQCC was found in 2006 at
Stanford University School

00:21:43.220 --> 00:21:45.920
of Medicine, together with
the state of California,

00:21:45.920 --> 00:21:49.670
in response to rising maternal
mortality and morbidity rates.

00:21:49.670 --> 00:21:52.070
Since CMQCC's
inception, California

00:21:52.070 --> 00:21:56.900
has seen a 55% decline in
our maternal mortality,

00:21:56.900 --> 00:22:01.280
between 2006 and
2013, at this time,

00:22:01.280 --> 00:22:03.020
where the national
maternal mortality

00:22:03.020 --> 00:22:04.850
rate continued to rise.

00:22:04.850 --> 00:22:07.490
Examples of our impact
include prevention

00:22:07.490 --> 00:22:12.650
of 120,000 early births
from 2009 to 2014,

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:17.210
with an increase of 8% of
births making its full term.

00:22:17.210 --> 00:22:21.530
A reduction of maternal
morbidity by about 21%

00:22:21.530 --> 00:22:26.150
between 2014 and '16,
among the 126 hospitals

00:22:26.150 --> 00:22:29.420
participating in our projects
to reduce maternal hemorrhage

00:22:29.420 --> 00:22:32.870
and preeclampsia, yet
there is more to our story.

00:22:32.870 --> 00:22:37.760
Since 1999, the data reporting
around maternal mortality

00:22:37.760 --> 00:22:40.820
in California show a
persistent three to four-fold

00:22:40.820 --> 00:22:43.310
gap between black
mothers and mothers

00:22:43.310 --> 00:22:45.110
from all other racial groups.

00:22:45.110 --> 00:22:47.030
Maternal mortality
rates nearly doubled

00:22:47.030 --> 00:22:52.910
for all racial ethnic groups
between, again, 1999 and 2006.

00:22:52.910 --> 00:22:58.710
In response, the CMQCC's founded
[INAUDIBLE] 2010 [INAUDIBLE]

00:22:58.710 --> 00:23:01.280
declined, showing a
decline in reduction

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:03.150
of maternal mortality.

00:23:03.150 --> 00:23:05.690
But the expectation was
that widespread adoption

00:23:05.690 --> 00:23:08.270
of clinical safety
bundles would reduce

00:23:08.270 --> 00:23:10.100
this gap in the number
of maternal deaths

00:23:10.100 --> 00:23:11.640
among black women.

00:23:11.640 --> 00:23:14.150
However, the difference in
outcomes for black mothers,

00:23:14.150 --> 00:23:17.420
compared with all other
racial groups, has persisted.

00:23:17.420 --> 00:23:20.600
Further analysis revealed
that clinical safety bundles

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:22.820
and social support
interventions,

00:23:22.820 --> 00:23:26.120
done in isolation, without
an integrated approach,

00:23:26.120 --> 00:23:28.580
did not produce the
desired outcomes.

00:23:28.580 --> 00:23:33.470
So CMQCC has now started
initiative with the California

00:23:33.470 --> 00:23:35.480
Birth Equity Collaborative.

00:23:35.480 --> 00:23:36.920
It really presents
an opportunity

00:23:36.920 --> 00:23:41.660
to develop these QI toolkits
within a hospital setting,

00:23:41.660 --> 00:23:46.430
again, to properly evaluate and
transform birth culture, care,

00:23:46.430 --> 00:23:49.640
experiences, and outcomes
through the integration

00:23:49.640 --> 00:23:52.790
of clinical and
sociocultural intervention

00:23:52.790 --> 00:23:55.070
and community-hospital
partnership.

00:23:55.070 --> 00:23:58.280
So our data show that, even in
the absence of risk factors,

00:23:58.280 --> 00:24:01.880
such as age over 35 years,
lack of health insurance,

00:24:01.880 --> 00:24:05.120
inadequate or no [INAUDIBLE],,
and less than a high school

00:24:05.120 --> 00:24:08.540
education, our US
health system continues

00:24:08.540 --> 00:24:11.120
to not be able to protect our
black mothers and [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:11.120 --> 00:24:14.240
people from experiencing
higher numbers of deaths

00:24:14.240 --> 00:24:16.430
and life-threatening
complications during pregnancy

00:24:16.430 --> 00:24:17.660
and childbirth.

00:24:17.660 --> 00:24:19.670
Again, increasing
evidence is pointing

00:24:19.670 --> 00:24:24.920
to racism within and across
multiple levels, and not race,

00:24:24.920 --> 00:24:27.680
as a key cause of these
birth disparities.

00:24:27.680 --> 00:24:30.800
Again, data also show
variations in the quality

00:24:30.800 --> 00:24:34.970
of care and outcomes between
and within [? racial groups ?]

00:24:34.970 --> 00:24:38.040
across hospitals in California,
highlighting [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:38.040 --> 00:24:42.350
opportunities for advancing
equity, as well as [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:42.350 --> 00:24:45.110
racism and quality improvement.

00:24:45.110 --> 00:24:48.590
So with our California Birth
Equity Collaborative pilot,

00:24:48.590 --> 00:24:51.410
CMQCC aims to
transform birth culture

00:24:51.410 --> 00:24:56.440
and care for, by, and with black
mothers and [INAUDIBLE] people

00:24:56.440 --> 00:25:00.470
in partnership with [INAUDIBLE]
community-based organizations,

00:25:00.470 --> 00:25:02.630
with our participating
hospitals,

00:25:02.630 --> 00:25:06.140
with local advisor groups being
formed back into the hospitals.

00:25:06.140 --> 00:25:08.700
As well as state and
national black women

00:25:08.700 --> 00:25:11.750
scholars serving as
pilot mentors, who

00:25:11.750 --> 00:25:14.720
represent various disciplines,
specifically public health

00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:16.575
and social sciences.

00:25:16.575 --> 00:25:17.950
TINA MARTIN: Thank
you very much.

00:25:17.950 --> 00:25:20.033
Dr. Scott, I'm just going
to throw it back to you.

00:25:20.033 --> 00:25:22.320
When you said racism
across all levels,

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:23.390
how does that translate?

00:25:23.390 --> 00:25:27.480
How does that play out for
a mother who has given birth

00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:29.670
or is giving birth, and
is looking for care?

00:25:29.670 --> 00:25:31.620
How does that play out?

00:25:31.620 --> 00:25:33.240
KAREN SCOTT: So
what we are seeing

00:25:33.240 --> 00:25:36.120
is that what is it
about the system?

00:25:36.120 --> 00:25:38.350
We're looking at
systems accountability.

00:25:38.350 --> 00:25:41.490
What is it about the system
that allows variation

00:25:41.490 --> 00:25:45.150
in the responsiveness
to a black mother who's

00:25:45.150 --> 00:25:48.980
reporting symptoms, that are
being dismissed, discounted,

00:25:48.980 --> 00:25:50.080
neglected?

00:25:50.080 --> 00:25:51.250
There's a delay.

00:25:51.250 --> 00:25:53.940
And why are we seeing
variation in the response, when

00:25:53.940 --> 00:25:58.470
we have science technology that
shows we're able to prevent

00:25:58.470 --> 00:26:00.420
60% of these causes?

00:26:00.420 --> 00:26:03.720
So we're wondering, what
is it about that response

00:26:03.720 --> 00:26:06.776
to black mothers, to
[INAUDIBLE] people

00:26:06.776 --> 00:26:09.540
that's causing these
variations with their systems?

00:26:09.540 --> 00:26:11.970
Where black people are
coming to the hospitals.

00:26:11.970 --> 00:26:14.970
They're educated, they have
health insurance in California.

00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:18.330
All of these factors that,
normally, are shown to protect

00:26:18.330 --> 00:26:20.260
are not doing that.

00:26:20.260 --> 00:26:23.590
So how [? we ?] look at the
ways in which interactions,

00:26:23.590 --> 00:26:27.000
communication, the counseling,
and the decision-making

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:30.150
as being inclusive
of black mothers,

00:26:30.150 --> 00:26:33.480
and their birthing support
systems, and people,

00:26:33.480 --> 00:26:36.420
in how health care
is being delivered.

00:26:36.420 --> 00:26:38.670
TINA MARTIN: And Susan, I
hear you listening intently.

00:26:38.670 --> 00:26:40.660
What is your response to
what Dr. Scott's saying?

00:26:40.660 --> 00:26:41.368
SUSAN MANN: Sure.

